50|$|He studied natural {{sciences}} at the universities of Würzburg and Munich, where his influences were Karl von Zittel and August Rothpletz. In 1899 he received his doctorate from Munich with a dissertation on <b>Eryops</b> megacephalus, titled Ein Beitrag zur Kenntnis von <b>Eryops</b> megacephalus. In 1903 he obtained his habilitation, and in 1908 became {{an associate professor at}} the university. In 1919 he was appointed director of the Staatssammlung fur Palaontologie und historische Geologie ("State Collection for Paleontology and Historical Geology") in Munich.|$|E
5000|$|The {{texture of}} <b>Eryops</b> skin was {{revealed}} by a fossilized [...] "mummy" [...] described in 1941. This mummy specimen {{showed that the}} body in life was covered in a pattern of oval bumps.|$|E
50|$|Proterogyrinus {{was similar}} in shape to other prehistoric amphibians, and reptiliomorphs, such as Crassigyrinus and <b>Eryops.</b> It {{was about two}} and a half meters (7-8 feet) long, similar in size to some of the biggest modern lizards.|$|E
